"YDNIW"в‰«$,$,$,$,$,@@

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Wind speed shaping the output. Run as-is and the program prints
  WINDY.

  How: "YDNIW" pushes 5 codepoints in reverse, so 'W' lands on top
  of the stack. Then в‰« raises speed to 2, and the second half is a
  1D obstacle course of $/, pairs:

      $   DROP    вЂ” tosses the top
      ,   PUT_CHR вЂ” pops the top and writes its codepoint as a char

  At speed 2 the IP only lands on every other cell. The layout puts
  every $ on an odd-index cell and every , on an even-index cell, so
  the IP hits all five `,`s and flies over all five `$`s, draining
  the stack cleanly into "WINDY". Without the speed boost the IP
  would visit every cell and the alternating $/, sequence would drop
  a letter for every one it prints вЂ” so wind speed is literally
  what makes the message reach stdout.

  Tick-by-tick:

    tick  cell        op            speed   stack                    out
    ----  ----------  ------------  -----   ----------------------   ---
     1    (0)  "      strmode on    1       []                       вЂ”
     2    (1)  Y      push 89       1       [89]                     вЂ”
     3    (2)  D      push 68       1       [89,68]                  вЂ”
     4    (3)  N      push 78       1       [89,68,78]               вЂ”
     5    (4)  I      push 73       1       [89,68,78,73]            вЂ”
     6    (5)  W      push 87       1       [89,68,78,73,87]         вЂ”
     7    (6)  "      strmode off   1       (no change)              вЂ”
     8    (7)  в‰«      speed += 1    2       (no change)              вЂ”
     9    (9)  ,      pop 87, putc  2       [89,68,78,73]            W
    10    (11) ,      pop 73, putc  2       [89,68,78]               I
    11    (13) ,      pop 78, putc  2       [89,68]                  N
    12    (15) ,      pop 68, putc  2       [89]                     D
    13    (17) ,      pop 89, putc  2       []                       Y
    14    (19) @      HALT          вЂ”       []                       вЂ”

  Ticks 9вЂ“13 advance by 2 columns each: the IP lands on columns 9,
  11, 13, 15, 17 вЂ” exactly the `,` cells. The `$` cells at columns
  8, 10, 12, 14, 16 are intermediate cells the IP flies over without
  decoding (SPEC В§3.7).

  The trailing @@ is there because the IP halts at column 19 (one
  past column 18) вЂ” speed-2 movement from (17) lands on (19).

  Things to play with:

    - Replace в‰« with в‰«в‰« to push speed to 3. The IP now lands on
      columns 10, 13, 16, 19, ... none of which carry `,`, so it
      prints nothing and falls into the trailing `@@`.

    - Add a в‰Є between two of the `,`s. At speed 2 the IP lands on
      в‰Є, drops to speed 1, and starts traversing every cell again
      вЂ” half the output is "WINDY"-style sampled, half is "$,$,..."
      mangled.

    - Trace it under `windy debug` and watch the `speed` row in the
      state panel jump from 1 to 2 the moment the IP visits в‰«.
